{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658400","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658400"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:47:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:47:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20746"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20746","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20746"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13622"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95802"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13622","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13622"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20746"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78581"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11653"},{"type":"tags","id":"11654"},{"type":"tags","id":"12612"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32758"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32759"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95802","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95802"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDifferent patterns of tissue necrosis have characteristic histopathological appearances that reflect their underlying pathogenic mechanisms.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the histopathological pattern of tissue necrosis caused by \u003Cem\u003EClostridium perfringens\u003C/em\u003E?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Coagulative necrosis with preserved architecture","Rapid tissue destruction with minimal inflammation","Liquefactive necrosis with purulent exudate","Caseous necrosis with granuloma formation","Fibrinoid necrosis of vessel walls"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERapid tissue destruction with minimal inflammation\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of clostridial myonecrosis (gas gangrene). \u003Cem\u003EClostridium perfringens\u003C/em\u003E produces potent toxins that directly destroy tissue through enzymatic activity, causing severe damage before significant inflammatory response can develop.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoagulative necrosis with preserved architecture\u003C/strong\u003E - Typically seen in hypoxic injury where protein denaturation preserves cellular outlines\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELiquefactive necrosis with purulent exudate\u003C/strong\u003E - Characteristic of neutrophil-rich bacterial infections and cerebral infarction\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECaseous necrosis with granuloma formation\u003C/strong\u003E - Associated with tuberculosis, showing cheese-like appearance with surrounding granulomas\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFibrinoid necrosis of vessel walls\u003C/strong\u003E - Seen in immune-mediated vasculitis with fibrin deposition\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe rapid progression and minimal inflammation of clostridial gangrene reflects the direct tissue-destructive effects of bacterial toxins rather than host inflammatory response.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Clostridial gangrene causes rapid tissue destruction with minimal initial inflammatory response due to potent bacterial toxins.","Different patterns of tissue necrosis have distinct histopathological appearances that reflect their underlying pathogenic mechanisms.","Clostridial toxins cause direct tissue damage through enzymatic activity rather than through inflammatory mediators."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 8; pages 348-349."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78581"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20746"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78581","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78581"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-29T20:08:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-29T20:09:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13622"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95802"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11653"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Infectious diseases","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":7,"createdAt":"2025-02-28T18:04:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-28T18:04:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11654","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11654"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"General principles of microbial pathogenesis","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2025-02-28T18:04:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-28T18:04:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12612","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12612"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Tissue necrosis","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"